<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> This alliance includes sparsely vegetated (<10% total vascular cover) areas with various species depending on the parent material (e.g., bedrock or lava field). The rocky substrate defines the type with little vascular vegetation cover, and instead non-vascular plants are characteristically present and variable in cover. This alliance occurs from California to Texas and adjacent Mexico (NatureServe 2019). Various maps in the Mojave and Sonoran deserts of California may use the name "sparsely vegetated rock outcrop" or the "cliff and outcrop group" designation for this alliance. Further sampling and analysis is needed to determine associations of this alliance, and to further differentiate this from other sparsely vegetated alliances.<br/>
<br/>
Fire fuels and ignition rates are naturally low in this alliance. Other disturbances, such as shifting rock, blow-outs, and erosion along cliffs and steep slopes are typical forces of change. Other impacts to this alliance come from human disturbance such as off-road vehicles and mining, though overall they likely have a low impact because barren areas occur across a large extent from the Mojave to Sonoran deserts in California. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> This alliance is found in the warm semi-deserts of North America, including the Mojave, Colorado, and Sonoran deserts in California, and Chihuahuan Desert beyond. </div>
</div>

	

    
